In its most fundamental form, fire transforms fuels in the presence of oxygen to complex gases and residues. Three components must be present for fires to burn: 1.) fuel, comprised of a variety of biomass materials including trees, branches, leaves or needles, grass, soil organic matter, peat, agricultural residues and dung, 2.) an ignition source and 3.) conditions that are conducive to burning (Krawchuk et al., 2009; Moritz et al., 2012; Forkel et al., 2017; Table 1, Fig. 2
                     ). Balch et al. (2018) term these components “switches”. Additional factors that determine the location and effects of the various fires on humans and ecosystems are the type of fire (e.g., uncontrolled versus intentional fire), the type of fuel and its arrangement and connectivity (e.g. is the fuel mainly in a tree canopy or is it distributed in piles or windrows awaiting burning after pruning or harvesting activities), type of combustion (flaming or smoldering), and several factors used to describe components of the “fire regime” of vegetation fires including the seasonality of burning, fire intensity and severity, fire behavior, fire size, fire frequency and a whole host of other complexities (Bond and Keeley, 2005; Bowman et al., 2009; Keeley, 2009; Keeley et al., 2009; Archibald et al., 2013; Scott et al., 2014; Archibald et al., 2018). These variables determine, in turn, which gases, aerosols and particulates are released to the atmosphere (Voulgarakis and Field, 2015), what residues are left behind as ash and partially charred material (Bodí et al., 2014; Plumlee et al., 2014; Zaccone et al., 2014), and what effects fires exert on ecosystems and the services they provide. Fires affect all four categories of ecosystem services defined by the Millennium Ecosystem Assessment (2005): provisioning, supporting, regulation and cultural services (Table 2
                     ).
